<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / MPs set to challenge Maastricht bill agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME MPs are set to challenge the amendments chosen for discussion at the
start of today's debate on the legislation to enact the Maastricht treaty.
They have complained that proper consideration of the terms of the
Maastricht agreement has been made harder because the bill - only four
clauses long - has been very difficult to amend.
Though more than 100 amendments have been tabled, not all are even eligible
for selection for debate by the Chair because they are beyond the scope of
the bill.
'When the 1972 act taking the UK into the Community started its committee
stage, points of order began at 3.30 in the afternoon and continued until
7.00 the following morning,' one Euro-sceptic recalled yesterday.
As a procedural device to allow debate on aspects of the treaty, the Labour
frontbench has put down a series of amendments to omit various sections of
the agreement. Though some of these are almost exactly the same as
amendments put forward by Euro-sceptics, the opposition business managers do
not plan to vote on most of them.
Labour does, however, intend to press for a vote on its amendments on
economic and monetary union and on the social chapter, but it would not
receive the support of Tory rebels.
Both the Labour Euro-sceptics and the Tory rebels have put down amendments
that would enable a referendum to take place. Other amendments would require
consent of the Commons before ratification or implementation of the treaty.
The decisions about which amendments will be allowed is critically important
to the rebels' chances of exerting any pressure on the government.
If progress is slow, not just today and tomorrow but on future days for the
committee stage, ministers may be forced to consider guillotining debate.
The danger is, however, that the opposition parties could combine with the
rebels to vote down a timetable.
</TEXT>
