<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Ombudsman attacks methods of investment sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INVESTMENT ombudsman yesterday strongly criticised selling methods in
the industry, saying that most disputes arose out of misunderstandings of
what clients had requested.
The ombudsman, Mr Richard Youard, said cases referred to him had decreased
slightly in the year to the end of March to 67, from 89 in the previous
year. The number of cases resolved rose slightly from 98 to 100. But there
had been a big increase in the amount paid out in compensation which rose
from Pounds 22,655 to Pounds 114,272. The largest amount paid in a
settlement was Pounds 25,031, up from Pounds 8,715 last year. About half the
cases were resolved in favour of the complainant.
Mr Youard said the fall in complaints - which contrasts with a marked
increase in criticism of banks, building societies and insurance companies -
was probably caused by the recession, which discouraged stock market
in-vestment while increasing reliance on banks and building societies.
In his criticism of selling methods, he referred to the lack of notes taken
at interviews by salesmen. 'It's quite possible for a salesman to be a
salesman and an adviser at the same time but it's difficult, and because a
salesman instinctively sells, things can go wrong.'
Mr Youard also criticised cost disclosure for unit-trust products. These
comments may have an impact on the Securities and Investments Board's review
of retail investment regulation, which has settled on disclosure rules for
life assurance, but has yet to make firm proposals on unit-trust disclosure.
The ombudsman claimed the 'health warning' on unit-trust marketing material,
which says that the price of units can go down as well as up, was
misunderstood, and should have greater prominence. He said: 'What in my
view, is required as a matter of urgency is the abandonment of the present
warning and its substitution in a prominent form by such words as 'you may
get back less than you invested'.'
He also found that the 'bid/offer' price-spread for unit trusts was
misunderstood. He said he would be delighted if the expression were
abandoned for ever 'since I have seen far too many cases where it has been
wholly misunderstood by the investor'. It should be substituted, he said,
with a simple statement that the cost of the manager's services, expressed
either as an amount of money or as a percentage, would be deducted from the
investment on the first day.
Mr Philip Warland, director general of the Unit Trust Association, said the
ombudsman was 'pushing against an open door'. He added: 'The UTA believes
that further simplification of pricing is desirable and we are at the moment
consulting our members.'
The investment ombudsman deals with disputes between customers and members
of Imro, the Investment Managers' Regulatory Office. The costs of running
the operation, which last year decreased slightly to Pounds 205,000, are
covered by Imro members.
</TEXT>
