<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Company failures at lowest for 18 months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of companies passing into administration and receivership in May
fell to the lowest level for 18 months.
Figures compiled from the official London and Edinburgh gazettes by Touche
Ross, the accountancy firm, show that banks made 358 insolvency appointments
last month, compared with 389 in March and 527 in February. The previous low
was 325 in December 1990.
Mr Christopher Morris, head of corporate special services at Touche Ross,
said the lower numbers probably reflected the bottoming out of the
recession. There were grounds for 'cautious optimism' on the number of
future corporate failures.
In the first five months of this year there were 2,306 appointments of
receivers or administrators, compared with 2,432 for the same period last
year. Coopers &amp; Lybrand received 345 appointments, Peat Marwick 271 and
Ernst &amp; Young 195.
The bank appointing most insolvency practitioners was National Westminster
with 482.
</TEXT>
