<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / BAe cuts satellite capacity and jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE is to halve its satellite manufacturing capacity with the
loss of up to 640 jobs. The cuts will be at the BAe Space Systems plant in
Stevenage, Hertfordshire, the only builder of commercial satellites in the
UK.
BAe blamed the job cuts on the loss of an order last week for a Japanese
satellite. That went to Hughes Aircraft of Los Angeles, the world's most
successful maker of communications satellites.
Mr David McLaurin, managing director of BAe's communications satellite
division, said: 'We regret having to make this announcement. However, it is
necessary to protect the business for the future and allow us to continue to
be competitive and effective.'
Staff will leave the factory between now and September 9. The company
yesterday called for volunteers, but said there could be compulsory
redundancies.
BAe has been under pressure for many months as orders in the increasingly
competitive communications satellite market have dried up. It has been in
talks since last summer with Anglo-French rival Matra Marconi Space over
merging the companies' satellite operations.
BAe has just completed three commercial contracts and is working on a
fourth. But next year contains only the probability of a contract from the
Ministry of Defence.
BAe is bidding to build Arabsat for the Arab League. If it wins, the number
of job cuts would be reduced by about 140. The winner of that contract
should be announced within three months, BAe said.
The company is a victim of increasing competition in the satellite industry.
The growth of the civil market has attracted new competitors from the
defence sector. At the same time, the proportion of contracts open to
competition has risen as international telephone traffic has increased.
Mr Tim Webb, national officer of the MSF general technical union, said the
announcement was another example of professionally qualified staff losing
their jobs due to government indifference. 'Unlike European partners the
government has given virtually no support to the UK space programme,' he
said.
</TEXT>
