<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Watchdog criticises World Service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Audit Office, the government spending watchdog, yesterday
called on the BBC World Service to improve its efficiency.
The report paid tribute to the World Service's independence and high
standard of broadcasting. It also found that the organisation - which
broadcasts in 38 languages to an audience of 120m - had 'a generally
satisfactory system of resource planning and financial management, and had
developed comprehensive procedures to assess the effectiveness of its
output'.
The watchdog called for: Further apportioning of overheads to individual
services to improve decision-making.
The continuation of improvements to weak cash flow forecasting. Further
improvements in the use of studios and in deploying studio managers. Greater
use of appraisal techniques to justify capital spending.
Further assessment of the impact of the Pounds 166m spent over the past 10
years to improve the audibility of broadcasts.
The NAO also argued that the World Service might be given more authority to
vary the amount of broadcast time, as long as this did not cost more.
The Foreign Office paid Pounds 143m to fund the World Service in 1991-92 -
not including Pounds 16m for monitoring other foreign broadcasts. At the
moment the number of hours broadcast in particular languages is set out
formally after negotiations between the Foreign Office and the BBC.
The NAO also said it would like to see the World Service move into profit on
its commercial activities.
Management of the BBC World Service. HMSO. Pounds 7.
</TEXT>
