<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Accounts disclose directors' payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES are beginning to disclose more information on directors'
responsibilities and rewards, according to the latest issue of Company
Reporting, the Edinburgh-based monitoring service of annual accounts.
Reports from Smithkline Beecham, the pharmaceuticals group; Tesco, the
supermarket group; Guinness, and Pearson, which owns the Financial Times,
have published information on directors' remuneration including
performance-related incentive payments, it notes.
Other groups, including Grand Metropolitan, Imperial Chemical Industries,
Sedgwick, BICC, First Leisure and Lonrho have already produced statements on
corporate governance and directors' responsibilities, but provide little
information on how directors are paid.
The details come at a time when the Cadbury Committee on financial aspects
of corporate governance recommended full disclosure of the calculation of
performance-related pay.
Company Reporting also notes that companies are beginning to introduce
cashflow information in their accounts in advance of the Financial Reporting
Standard on cashflow statements, which came into effect in March this year.
It concludes from a sample of 400 companies' annual reports produced since
the standard was issued last September, that more than 29 per cent have
adopted the new standard.
Company Reporting. 68 Dundas Street, Edinburgh EH3 6QZ. Annual subscription
Pounds 315.
</TEXT>
