<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / World Trade News: Director urges Europe to welcome Japanese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S leading manufacturers should not be barred from Europe: instead they
should be 'firmly inside Europe as role models', according to Mr Walter
Eltis, director general of the London-based national economic development
office.
In a presentation to the Institut de L'Entreprise in Paris yesterday, Mr
Eltis argued that Europe could learn valuable lessons from British
experience over the past decade in attracting Japanese investors to
transform ailing physics-based industries such as electronics, television
and car manufacture.
Efforts through the 1960s and 1970s to protect the British motor industry
led to the creation of 'a combine which by 1986 was losing Pounds 1bn a year
to produce not very many not very good cars,' he recalls.
He warns that the comparatively poor recent performance of groups like Fiat
and Renault is due to heavy reliance on protected local markets: 'If the
policy of continental Europe is the same as Britain's it will welcome
Japanese manufacturers where (their) competitive edge is exceptional, even
if this leads to the total elimination of the previous producers.
'The ideal way to remedy industrial weaknesses is to get the world's best
into the economy, and to learn from them with the greatest possible
rapidity.'
</TEXT>
