<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 92 / Earth Summit cost estimated at Dollars 37m: Conference seen
as chance to improve Brazil's poor environmental image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL is footing the bill for what promises to be the biggest party on
earth. Mr Flavio Perri, the conference organiser, estimates the total cost
to the government at Cr105bn (Dollars 37m) - a drain on a bankrupt Treasury
and a country where even the presidency no longer serves coffee.
The Brazilians have even had to bear the travel expenses of some of their
guests and have so far paid out more than Dollars 2m for UN officials.
Mr Marcos Azambuja, Brazil's main negotiator, believes the money has been
well spent. He sees the Earth Summit as a chance to improve the country's
poor image in terms of environment and security. He also hopes it will put
Rio de Janeiro back on the map as a key tourist destination and a future
international conference centre.
But he says Brazil's parlous economic situation means that organisation has
had to be done on the cheap. 'Like anyone inviting friends to dinner, we'd
like to offer more to impress.' In fact, just three months before the
conference, the budget was halved.
The main outlay was on extending Rio's communications network and improving
security. The conference centre, which had been used only for exhibitions
and rock concerts, had to be renovated. Translation services have been
installed and an enormous round table for heads of state built. So stretched
was the Brazilian purse that its own delegation is housed in a
pre-fabricated unit with no roof. Other delegations enjoy air conditioning
and carpets.
Brazil has accepted donations from the private sector: 285 cars from
Volkswagen and 10 buses from Scania. The federal police chipped in, lending
300 cars.
The real cost has lain with the Rio state government, which has been hard at
work painting and resurfacing roads, restoring parks and installing
streetlighting.
Mr Roberto D'Avila, the state environment secretary, estimates that the
state has spent Dollars 500m but he says this was for already-needed
investments. 'Hosting such a big event meant that priorities became
super-priorities and things which had waited for 20 years only happened
because of the summit'. He gives as examples renovation of the airport and
new highway construction.
The influx of about 30,000 visitors is stimulating the private sector,
causing one Rio shopkeeper to comment yesterday: 'We are starting to like
this green movement. To us green means dollars.'
</TEXT>
