<DATE>920602
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / International Company News: Warner fails to commit to Sony
Mini Disc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WARNER Music Group, a division of US entertainment giant Time Warner, has
declined to commit its roster of artists to the new Mini Disc audio
technology format being developed by Sony of Japan.
Mini Disc is a portable recording and playback system which Sony is due to
launch in Japan in November and which it hopes will eventually become the
main successor to the analog cassette tape.
In a statement, Warner said it was still addressing the relative merits of
Mini Disc and its main rival, the digital compact cassette being developed
by Dutch group Philips.
Sony was putting on a brave face yesterday. A spokesman in New York said:
'We are happy that Warner is reviewing the two technologies equally.'
Warner is reluctant to commit itself to the new digital technology because
of concern that new formats may crimp the growth of compact discs (CDs)and
to a lesser extent, cassette tapes.
Mr Robert Morgado, in his role as chairman of Warner Music Group, said:
'Compact Disc is the premier carrier for the music industry and we are
asking manufacturers to assure us that their new technologies do not
adversely impact CDs continued growth.'
The decision by Warner not to back the Mini Disc is a blow to Sony's hopes
for the product. In order for Mini Disc to succeed, Sony must offer a wide
range of music titles to potential buyers of Mini Disc players when the
product enters the market later this year. Yet so far only two big labels,
EMI Music and Sony's own music division, have signed up with Mini Disc.
Sony had hoped Warner with its powerful roster of stars including Madonna
and Rod Stewart, would prove an important recruit.
To date, Philip's digital compact cassette format appears to have a head
start on Sony's Mini Disc. It has already won artist commitments from the
six biggest labels in the music industry for the product's September launch.
</TEXT>
