<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / Big Six hit by recession and competition: Accountancy firms
cut staff - Audit work suffers / Growth in insolvency work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECESSION and competition sharply reduced fee income growth in most of
Britain's six largest accountancy firms, according to figures for the year
to April 1992 released yesterday.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand remained the largest UK firm with fee income of Pounds
577m in the year to April 30, but also registered the only absolute decline,
with revenues down by 1.87 per cent.
All the top firms except Arthur Andersen cut professional staff including
partners by between 7 per cent and 10 per cent, reflecting the widespread
redundancies in the last few months.
Income from three of Coopers' divisions - audit, management consultancy and
tax - all declined, while insolvency income rose by 16 per cent. But the
firm said last year's reported Pounds 588m income had been adjusted
downwards to Pounds 577m, reflecting difficulties in calculation after the
merger with Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells. The name Deloitte was also officially
dropped yesterday.
Strongest growth came from Arthur Andersen, mainly as a result of a 30 per
cent increase from Andersen Consulting. 'We're working with major
organisations which believe there's going to be a better tomorrow,' said Mr
Keith Burgess, head of the consulting arm.
Touche Ross also grew sharply, with income up by 15.7 per cent. Mr John
Roques, senior partner, said the increase reflected work referred from its
network of firms overseas, particularly in the USA and Japan, growing
consultancy work in Europe, and advice to medium-sized companies.
Revenue growth in the remaining firms - KPMG Peat Marwick, Ernst &amp; Young,
and Price Waterhouse - was boosted by insolvency work but struggled to beat
inflation.
Mr Ian Brindle, senior partner of Price Waterhouse, said audit work was
suffering because of recession, overcapacity and intense competition.
However, none of the firms is willing to provide details of costs or profits
distributed to partners, stressing their legal status as partnerships does
not require them to do so.
They also argue it is very difficult to compare firms, which have different
year-ends and sometimes exclude income from regions such as the Channel
Islands. They say that some - particularly Andersen Consulting - operate in
distinctive markets and are not direct competitors.
Most of the managers in the firms suggested that the rapid income growth
experienced during the 1980s was unlikely to be repeated in the near future.
'Double-digit growth will tend to be a thing of the past,' said Mr Elwyn
Eilledge, senior partner of Ernst &amp; Young. 'We are concentrating now on
managing the numbers to suit our business.'
Lex, Page 20
