FT  02 JUN 92 / Business school director resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Tom Cannon resigned yesterday as director of Manchester Business
School, clearing the way for controversial plans by Manchester University to
change the structure of management research and education in the city.
The plans have already caused 14 private-sector representatives to resign
from the business school's council. They demanded an inquiry by Mr John
Patten, the education secretary. With Prof Cannon no longer available to
lead the school's fight for greater autonomy from the university, Mr Patten
is thought unlikely to intervene.
Prof Cannon and the university yesterday agreed a statement to reduce the
blow to the university's prestige caused by the high-level resignations -
which were led by Sir Dennis Landau, chief executive of the Co-operative
Wholesale Society.
Prof Cannon, who had two years of his contract still to run, said a recent
sabbatical had given him the chance to look into new areas of research which
he would now pursue. The university appointed him to a part-time visiting
chair in corporate responsibility.
The university plans to federate the management education and research
activities of the business school, the University of Manchester Institute of
Science and Technology (Umist) and the university's department of
accounting. They have sofar operated separately.
Prof Cannon said a new ordinance brought in by the university to regularise
financial accountability would alter the remit of the school's director and
its council.
The ordinance will in effect remove the business school's autonomy and
abolish its council. The council's 14 lay members, who resigned, say the
university does not understand the relationship needed between the public
and private sectors in management education, which requires more autonomy
from the university, not less.
The university admitted in the joint statement with Prof Cannon that its
relations with the business school have been difficult for many years - and
well before Prof Cannon's arrival in 1989. It says they were forced into new
prominence by the Education Reform Act, which required the university to
define clearer lines of financial accountability.
In what amounts to a public testimonial for Prof Cannon, the university says
he doubled the size of the school, attracted record numbers of postgraduate
students, improved the quality of its research, enhanced its academic
reputation and achieved two years of record profits.
</TEXT>
