<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / Routes to being considered for an honour
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WHITEHALL MACHINE:  technically anybody can make a recommendation, but
most come through the Civil Service grapevine. Each principal department has
a subcommittee that sifts names and forwards them to a central honours pool
run by the Cabinet Office. Names are then passed to 10 Downing Street and
eventually to Buckingham Palace.
THE QUEEN: has her own list for the Order of Merit and for some orders of
chivalry.
POLITICAL PARTIES: the principal route is through the whips' offices.
Conservative Central Office feeds candidates to the chief whip - one of
whose titles is patronage secretary - and after sifting they go to the
Cabinet Office and on to 10 Downing Street. Nominations from opposition
parties go the same way.
THE PRIME MINISTER: can add or subtract from the lists the Civil Service
supplies, and it is at that stage that glamour names, such as pop and sports
stars, are added.
</TEXT>
