<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / Warning by Bank on foreign mergers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England warned banks yesterday of the dangers of buying a
foreign bank or trying to develop into pan-European institutions.
The management and cultural impediments of adopting either strategy 'appear
to be overly daunting', Mr Brian Quinn, the Bank's director in charge of
supervision, told chairmen of the world's biggest banks at the International
Monetary Conference in Toronto.
This year's conference chairman is Mr William Purves, chairman of Hongkong
and Shanghai Banking Corporation, the Far Eastern bank that is trying to buy
Midland Bank of the UK.
Mr Quinn said cross-border deals similar to that proposed by Hongkong Bank
would remain few and far between.
He said it was 'unlikely that we will see any pan-European retail or
wholesale bank or securities company established in the near future'.
Mr Quinn pointed out that banks of different nationalities were tending to
form looser alliances, such as sharing businesses. Some were taking minority
shareholdings in each other or being jointly represented in some countries.
He was sceptical about the benefits of such alliances. 'They appear to owe
more to defensive or protective sentiments than to a clearly articulated
strategy,' he said.
Big US banks were encouraged by a speech from Mr Nicholas Brady, the US
Secretary of the Treasury, in which he made a commitment to revive the White
House attempts to reform the US banking system. 'Banks should be permitted
to branch nationwide, diversifying their risk and increasing the competition
in service.'
</TEXT>
