FT  02 JUN 92 / Concern at 'fragility' of training policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER evidence of govern-ment concern at the 'fragility' of its training
policy is disclosed in a strategy paper by Sir Geoffrey Holland, permanent
secretary at the Department of Employment.
He says the 'initial enthusiasm' of the 82 Training and Enterprise Councils
in England and Wales has been 'dented' and adds that not all Tecs are fully
effective. The main anxiety mentioned in the paper is the ability of Tecs to
work with the education service and meet the government's targets for skill
levels among young people. 'There is a big (but declining) gap between the
achievements of young people and the target achievement,' the paper adds.
Sir Geoffrey says that a shortage of resources has prevented Tecs from
playing a full part in stimulating growth in the Investors In People scheme.
'We need to address ourselves to how to transform IIP into the flagship it
ought to be - and must be if we are to succeed,' he writes.
On an institutional level the paper states: 'Tecs clearly need to develop
rapidly and professionally their partnership with education . . . Few have
made much progress in this area.'
Sir Geoffrey also highlights the tension between meeting government training
guarantees for the unemployed and achieving training targets for those in
work. That has been echoed by many Tec chairmen, some of whom would like the
freedom to transfer resources from the large schemes for the unemployed -
Youth Training and Employment Training - to other training initiatives.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow employment secretary, called for a thorough
stocktaking of the success and failure of the Tec experiment but expressed
opposition to any move to shift resources away from training the unemployed.
