<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / Chambers offered single roof: Moves to merge two business
organisations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON THE brink of the 21st century, the business organisations that have
represented British companies since the end of the 19th are belatedly
bringing themselves up to date.
Plans for a merger between the Association of British Chambers of Commerce -
founded in 1860 - and the National Chamber of Trade - established in 1895 -
mark an important step towards consolidating the voice of smaller
businesses. Their fragmented lobbying efforts have frequently been blamed
for their ineffectiveness in influencing government policy.
A merger would also represent an important boost to plans launched by the
association just over 18 months ago to strengthen the chamber of commerce
network. By linking with the NCT, which mainly represents retailers, the
association would enhance its role as one of the country's big three
national business groups, second to the Confederation of British Industry
with 250,000 members and ahead of the Institute of Directors with 33,500 UK
members.
If the merger - in effect a takeover by the association of the less
financially well endowed NCT - goes ahead in the autumn, it will end the
confusion of two very similarly named organisations competing for public
attention and for members in towns and cities up and down the country.
The NCT draws a large chunk of its membership from 28 affiliated trade
organisations representing among others booksellers, coal merchants and
sports goods distributors. It also has 150 chambers around the country.
The association heads a group of more than 100 chambers but is trying to
improve patchy national coverage by creating a network of 55 core chambers.
Around those will cluster smaller local chambers, some of them no more than
social clubs.
For the NCT, difficulties are even more acute. Average membership of local
chambers of trade is 60 people. Even the largest six chambers of trade in
towns such as Sheffield, Carlisle and Eastbourne have only 400 to 500
members. That compares with the larger chambers of commerce in London and
Birmingham with 5,000 and 5,400 members respectively - although even those
are tiny compared with the large, publicly funded Continental chambers. None
of the chambers of trade is expected to have the resources to join the the
association's core network.
Both the association and the NCT have to cope with unaffiliated chambers
that use the chamber title but are outside national membership for financial
reasons or because they have fallen out with the national body.
Although at first sight the addition of 150,000 new members to the
association would be welcome to an organisation in the middle of a national
recruitment drive to boost numbers from 83,000 to 150,000, many of the new
members would be one-person businesses and corner shops. They do not conform
to the association's target of dynamic businesses set on growth.
They would, however, be welcome at a time when the association's own
expansion programme has run up against the recession. With the impact of its
recruitment drive yet to show through, the association is nursing a 7,000
loss in membership over the past two years.
The association and the NCT have been trying for many years to merge. The
two most recent attempts, in 1984 and 1986-87, failed because of differences
of opinion about the relative weight of the two organisations in the
combined group.
So why do they now think they can get together? Mr Bernard Tennant, NCT
director-general, believes it is because the association wants to fill an
important gap in its coverage of UK industry sectors, namely retailing.
The NCT is willing to accept a subordinate role as a retailing and small
firms division of the association, prompted possibly by the sharp
contraction in the number of smaller retailers in recent years - although
not in its membership - and by financial constraints.
The NCT still has a strong balance sheet but has made operating losses in
the past two years because of a reluctance by member chambers to raise
subscription rates.
The association's reorganisation is being led by Mr Ron Taylor, a former
head of Leeds chamber of commerce and the organisation's first
director-general in living memory to have a chamber rather than a Civil
Service background.
Mr Tennant is a long-term member of the NCT's headquarters staff, who became
director-general in 1987. The two men have known each other since the 1960s,
when Mr Tennant also worked for the chambers of commerce.
He later headed Bolton's chamber of trade, which, wealthier than the local
chamber of commerce, invited the latter to take office space in its new
headquarters. As the terms of the proposed merger suggest, that power
relationship has changed.
</TEXT>
