<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / International league of awards led by Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and ANDREW SLADE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN LEADS the international league in the diversity of honours and the
automatic way they are awarded in certain sectors, notably the Civil
Service.
The US president gives out 'medals of freedom' and Congress has a few awards
for people engaged in 'conspicuous good works'. As one US embassy official
put it, however, the granting of such honours is a 'rarity, not a routine'.
France's Legion d'Honneur was created by Napoleon in 1802, and has five
grades: chevaliers (knights), officiers, commandeurs, grands officiers and
grand-croix.
In peacetime, to become a knight, 20 years' service is required by civil
servants and armed forces personnel, or 25 years in professional service.
The medals handed out are not as numerous as in Napoleon's time, and numbers
of recipients for the top four grades are strictly limited.
Although the legion is awarded by the president, its grades are strictly
separated and regulated. Chevaliers can become officiers only after they
have been a chevalier for eight years; commandeurs must be an officier for
five years; grands officers must be commandeurs for three years; and holders
of the grand-croix must have held the rank of grand officier for three
years.
The order cannot be awarded to serving parliamentarians during their term of
office; neither can they be promoted during that time, unless as a result of
military service.
There is a Bastille Day - July 14 - honours list. Last year, recipients
included jazz trumpeter Miles Davis and actress Sophia Loren (both made
knights), and US Gulf war commander General Norman Schwarzkopf, who became a
grand officier.
More controversially, Lt Col (then Major) Alain Mafart, a member of a French
secret service team convicted of bombing the Greenpeace ship Rainbow Warrior
in Auckland harbour in 1985, was created chevalier in July last year.
Protests from New Zealand were brushed off with a French statement that
almost everyone with the appropriate service receives the award.
Germany brought in its honours system in 1949 with the creation of the
federal republic. Like France, it has one main award - the Federal Cross of
Merit - with varying grades.
In Spain, King Juan Carlos can create hereditary marqueses, dukes and
counts. He has created 18 such grand titles since becoming king in 1976.
Recipients include musicians, intellectuals, and democratically elected
politicians.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
