FT  02 JUN 92 / Canadians to tackle impasse in unity talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN federal and provincial officials will spend the next week seeking
to break an impasse in protracted national unity talks aimed at forestalling
the separatist movement in Quebec.
Talks broke off at the weekend with deep rifts among the nine
English-speaking provinces. Failure to break the deadlock soon may leave Mr
Brian Mulroney, prime minister, with little choice but to call a national
referendum on the federal government's favoured proposals.
Mr Joe Clark, constitutional affairs minister, and his provincial
counterparts had met over the past three months in an attempt to craft a new
constitution before a self-imposed deadline of May 31.
Ottawa is keen to present a package of constitutional reforms to Quebec well
before October, when the Francophone province is scheduled to hold its own
referendum. Although support for independence has recently waned, there is
concern that separatist fervour could be reignited by failure among the
other nine provinces to agree a package acceptable to Quebec.
Among the thorniest issues is reform of the Senate, the upper house of
parliament. There is consensus that the body, which at present consists
entirely of appointed members, should be elected.
But several western and Atlantic provinces, led by Alberta, are pushing  -
against opposition from Ontario and Quebec - for a body with wide powers and
equal representation from each province. Alberta insists it will not accede
to some of Quebec's key demands unless its Senate reform proposals are
accepted.
The federal government, which is keen to bring negotiations to a decisive
end, has been pressing ahead with preparations for a national referendum, a
last-ditch solution. Parliament passed an enabling bill last month and the
government has launched a national advertising blitz aimed at promoting
national unity.
</TEXT>
