FT  02 JUN 92 / Amnesty critical of Peru regime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Latin America Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMNESTY International, the human rights group, said yesterday that human
rights violations had continued in Peru since President Alberto Fujimori
took power nearly two years ago, writes Stephen Fidler, Latin America
Editor.
'Widespread 'disappearances' and extra-judicial executions by the security
forces, as well as torture, continued to be the organisation's principal
concerns in Peru,' it said.
In the first 21 months of the Fujimori government, 392 people reported as
'disappeared' remained unaccounted for after arrest. There were 169
extra-judicial executions.
The group was also critical of measures taken since Mr Fujimori dissolved
Congress on April 5, which it said undermined the structures by which the
state made provision for protection of human rights. However, it reiterated
concern about the killing of hundreds of defenceless people by opposition
groups.
