<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 92 / Eurofighter heads for German crash-landing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S aerospace industry has made serious tactical blunders in its
campaign to participate in building the European fighter aircraft (EFA), and
now has virtually no chance of winning a majority for the project in the
Bundestag, according to a leading parliamentary defence spokesman.
Dr Werner Hoyer, the defence expert for the Free Democrats (FDP) in the
Bundestag, warned that the issue would be decided on an emotional, not a
factual basis. He is one of the six-man working group which met last night
to recommend the degree of Germany's future participation in the project.
In an interview shortly beforehand, he said there was no hope of putting
together a parliamentary majority in favour of allocating more funds to the
EFA project next year in the current climate of budget cuts.
The deep disagreements about the aircraft within the governing German
coalition were made clear yesterday when two leading politicians differed
fundamentally over what should be done.
Mr Erich Riedl, a member of the Bavaria-based Christian Social Union (CSU)
and state secretary in the Economics Ministry, said tens of thousands of
jobs in the German aerospace industry would be lost if Germany pulled out of
the project. 'Every politician thinks he will win elections at home if he is
against the EFA,' he said in a radio interview. 'But it is wrong, even
irresponsible, to think like that.'
The opposite viewpoint was put by Mr Peter Hintze, newly appointed as
secretary-general of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats (CDU). He
said the EFA was not appropriate 'in the changed financial and security
situation in a united Germany'.
The CSU has succeeded in having a decision on the project deferred, with
tomorrow's joint meeting of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group postponed to
June 16.
Dr Hoyer believes that in spite of the delay, the fate of German
participation is sealed. 'The decisive point in our report is whether the
working group recommends, or whether the defence minister recommends,
allocating some DM100m (Pounds 34m) in the 1993 budget for pre-production
costs (for EFA), to purchase the tools needed for later construction,' Dr
Hoyer said. 'The industry insists these tools will be needed.
'The decision to put this into the budget will be seen as a point of no
return. But there is no majority in the Bundestag in favour.
'It is a catastrophic mistake by the German (aerospace) industry to have
insisted on this. They thought they could get a positive decision now.'
Dr Hoyer said that no alternative aircraft should be automatically excluded.
They include the US F-16 and F-18, the Swedish Gripen, and the Russian
MiG-29. However, he said he would not vote for any solution which would be
more expensive than the EFA.
The German aerospace industry, led by Daimler-Benz, argues that any
alternative would be more expensive than the EFA, because the input of
German industry, and the taxes repaid to the government, would be far lower
with an imported aircraft.
</TEXT>
