FT  01 JUN 92 / RBC may lose up to CDollars 300m on O&amp;Y loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL Bank of Canada has added CDollars 300m (Pounds 138m) to its loan-loss
provisions to cover expected losses on the O&amp;Y portfolio and some other
problem accounts. However, this write-down has been offset by an equal
reduction in provisions for Third World loans, thus containing the fall in
second-quarter earnings to 8 per cent.
RBC, Canada's biggest financial institution, said it has classified
two-thirds of its CDollars 780m exposure to O&amp;Y as non-performing, resulting
in a 45 per cent jump in non-accrual loans over the past year to CDollars
2.7bn. It still expects its net loan losses for the year to be CDollars
740m. The net second-quarter provision was CDollars 185m, up from CDollars
155m a year earlier.
Earnings slipped to CDollars 212.3m, or 59 cents a share, in the three
months to April 30, from CDollars 230m, or 69 cents a share, a year earlier.
Net interest income edged up to just over CDollars 1bn from CDollars 977m.
Canada's six big banks have disclosed a total exposure to O&amp;Y of CDollars
3.1bn. Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, the ailing developer's biggest
creditor, has taken a special charge of CDollars 1bn. Bank of Montreal,
which says its loans to O&amp;Y are secured, has left its estimate of loan
losses unchanged for fiscal 1992. Like RBC, Bank of Nova Scotia cushioned
the O&amp;Y blow, using Third World writedowns.
London's riverbus, Page 6
US property market, Page 19
Observer, Page 15
