<TEXT>
The cleverest man I have known, and one of the wisest, was Sir Peter
Medawar. On the subject of human population he told me there was only one
certainty: people would worry, either because there were too many births or,
as in France after the Fist World War, too few. His wife, however, had no
doubts about the perils of population explosion: she ran the International
Planned Parenthood Federation. It was bumping into my headmaster, the father
of umpteen children, at one of her IPPF functions (inviting him had been my
idea of a joke) which led eventually to my expulsion from school . . . but I
digress. Horizon (8.10 BBC2) considers global population growth and asks the
crucial questions: when will the population reach the carrying capacity of
the planet and what happens then?
Few current affairs programmes have achieved as much pre-transmission
ballyhoo as today's World In Action (8.30 ITV). It had better be good. The
first of two parts, it investigates the members of the International Olympic
Committee and especially the president, Juan Samaranch.
Panorama ponders the forthcoming Earth Summit in Rio (9.30 BBC1).
