<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Reform call for textiles industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TEXTILES industry in the Scottish Borders region needs radical
restructuring and an infusion of new capital and ideas if it is to survive,
say consultants appointed after a series of job losses in the industry.
Werner International, the consultants, urges the industry to make good a
long-term lack of investment in production equipment, to improve training
and to attract a younger labour force.
The consultants praise the quality of the area's textiles production, 70 per
cent of which is exported, but say weavers that persist with classic
Scottish products will have difficulty in surviving as tastes change and
Italian competition intensifies. They also warn that weaving companies are
vulnerable because they depend on a UK clothing market that is in
'irreversible contraction'.
Spinning companies should be able to defend their position, the consultants
say. Knitwear will face growing competition from China, especially if
Japanese companies operating there improve the quality of Chinese knitwear.
Spinning, weaving and knitwear are the main industry in the Borders region,
employing 5,500 workers. The report was commissioned last year by Scottish
Borders Enterprise, the region's enterprise company, after numerous mill
closures and the loss in two years of 1,000 jobs.
Werner says smaller borders textile groups should approach Japanese, EC and
US textile companies to buy the Scottish companies or set up joint ventures
with them. Borders companies should themselves create larger groupings
through mergers.
Werner advises Scottish Borders Enterprise to promote the creation of
marketing companies to function as co-operatives, and to establish a product
development and design centre to provide consultancy services. Scottish
Borders Enterprise said at a conference of industry leaders in Galashiels,
Roxburghshire, last week that it would lead an initiative to encourage the
industry to change its ways.
The Werner report says that while larger companies are diversifying into
non-traditional products, smaller companies need to follow suit and to
develop stronger overseas marketing links.
The smaller knitwear companies need to adopt an 'industrial' rather than an
'artisanal' approach to manufacturing, the consultants say.
The consultants found that only two Borders knitwear companies employ
workers of the youngest employable generation, with the others relying on
highly skilled older workers. Efforts must be made to recruit and train a
new generation of textile workers, the consultants say.
A Strategic Plan for the Textile Industries in the Scottish Borders.
Scottish Borders Enterprise, Galashiels, Borders, Scotland.
</TEXT>
