   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERSHIP of the Nupe public-service union yesterday won the backing of
its annual conference for plans to merge with the Nalgo and Cohse unions.
The proposals, which aim to create Britain's biggest union with 1.5m
members, were supported less enthusiastically than expected.
The 4,980 to 3,099 vote suggested that the merger, which will be decided in
a ballot of all the members of the three unions, is not a foregone
conclusion.
Some delegates were concerned about the likely resistance of any Nalgo
members to affiliating to the Labour party. Nalgo is not affiliated, whereas
Cohse and Nupe are. Other delegates said there might be defections to other
largely blue-collar unions.
The proposals will face a stronger test in a fortnight when Nalgo's annual
conference votes on them.
The National Union of Journalists was threatened with defections yesterday
after one of its largest office branches voted against staying in the
organisation.
Members of the 288-strong Daily Mirror chapel decided by 94 votes to 76 not
to stay in the union.
One possibility is that they will join the British Association of
Journalists, which is being set up by Mr Steve Turner, a former Daily Mirror
journalist who was dismissed as NUJ general secretary last year after
clashes with the union's executive.
