<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / Talks on Ulster to reopen today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR PATRICK MAYHEW, Northern Ireland secretary, faces a tough meeting with
the province's political leaders today that may decide the future of the
government's latest attempt to resolve political differences by dialogue.
If a dispute between unionist and nationalist leaders over procedure cannot
be resolved, Sir Patrick will soon face the choice of imposing his own
decision or shelving the five-week-old initiative.
A sub-committee set up last week to resolve the differences appears to have
made some headway, but it is unclear whether its proposals will be
acceptable to party leaders.
The row is over when to move from debate on government in the province to
the planned second 'strand' of talks - the point at which the Irish
government would enter to discuss Northern Ireland's relations with the
south.
Sir Patrick is expected to be less tolerant of delays than his predecessor,
Mr Peter Brooke. He may decide to force the pace - by deciding unilaterally
on a date for strand two, for instance - or to suspend the initiative in the
hope that it could be revived later.
Even if a solution is found, the gloom surrounding the talks is a setback
for government hopes that distrust between nationalists and unionists had
eased sufficiently for an agreement on new political structures in the
province.
Mr James Molyneaux and the Rev Ian Paisley, the two unionist leaders, are
understood to be worried at the nationalist Social Democratic and Labour
party's proposals for giving the Irish government a role in the affairs of
Northern Ireland.
Many in the SDLP believe the unionists are deliberately delaying progress
because of their nervousness about talking to the Irish government.
