<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / University decides to stick to the federation trail: The row
over department mergers at Manchester
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER University is expected to go ahead with a plan to federate the
separate management research and education activities of Manchester Business
School, University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology (Umist)
and the university's department of accounting unless Mr John Patten, the
education secretary, intervenes.
The move will be in spite of the resignation of 14 senior business leaders
of the business school's council. They allege that the university does not
understand the nature of the partnership needed for successful management
education between business and academic skills.
The 14 executives are led by Sir Dennis Landau, chief executive of the
Co-operative Wholesale Society. They include Sir Peter Middleton, chairman
of Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the investment bank, and a former Treasury
permanent secretary. The 14 have asked Mr Patten to step in. They want
Manchester Business School to enjoy similar autonomy from its parent
university as London Business School, which was set up at the same time in
the mid 1960s after the Franks report had called for management education to
be improved. The council would govern it.
Manchester University, however, wants to pull together the three disparate
strands of business and management education and research and try to create
a world-class institution with about 150 staff. The proposed institution
would build on existing and extensive links and collaboration with industry.
The present row has surfaced after 10 years of growing tension. 'Someone
should have knocked all the heads together about five years ago,' one former
member of the business school faculty said yesterday.
There have been two sources of tension - one between the university and the
business school, and the other within the school itself. The latter lies in
a clash between academic and vocational views of management education and
research.
Some staff are highly qualified academics with strings of publications to
their names, while others are more practical in their approach, with less of
an academic background but contributing their experience to the job.
The depth of the split in the school is shown by the faculty's vote on
whether to support the plan for federation. The university has emphasised
that 'a majority' favoured its plan, but voting was 29 to 28, with some of
the more vocationally based staff worried about their career prospects if
more emphasis were placed on academic rather than practical achievement.
The split between the academic and vocational approaches is mirrored in the
tension between the school and the university. Another academic involved
says the university is jealous of its reputation as the 'Oxford of the
north'. 'There is a lot of snootiness about the backgrounds of some members
of the school's staff,' he says.
The annual research ratings of the government's Universities Funding Council
have intensified the conflict, with the business school scoring only three
out of five, based on such criteria as quality of research and international
publications.
Umist has scored four or five out of five in recent assessments, while the
department of accounting - part of the university's faculty of economics and
social science - has also been doing better than the business school.
Umist, which grew out the 19th-century Manchester Mechanics' Institute and
has a self-governing status separate from the university which the business
school covets, is also understood to be not entirely happy with the
university's plans because its own management school is a principal pillar
of Umist's structure.
However, it has already agreed to offer joint engineering degrees with its
university departmental counterparts and appears to have bowed to the
inevitable, with the federation idea an uneasy compromise short of full
integration.
Tensions in the business school have affected morale. Professor Roy Payne,
who is widely respected for his work on organisational structure and
behaviour, grew weary of the politics and resigned as dean last year. He now
has a chair at Sheffield University.
The future of Professor Tom Cannon, the school's director, is in doubt.
University insiders say he will announce his departure when he returns from
study leave this week. He has two years of a five-year contract still to run
and has managed the school profitably.
Prof Cannon, a well-known researcher on small business, was originally
expected to come down on the academic side of the argument and support
integration. He fought instead for more autonomy and the right to appoint
any staff he felt were needed.
'He has done nothing wrong, so he can't be sacked,' one insider said
yesterday. 'If he goes, it will be because they have come to an arrangement
to buy him out so the university can have its way.'
</TEXT>
