FT  01 JUN 92 / Closure threat to two north-east coal mines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO coal mines in north-east England may close shortly, leaving only three
working pits in the region.
Easington, in County Durham, faces a review that will decide its future, and
nearby Vane Tempest, near Newcastle upon Tyne, will be reviewed shortly
afterwards. If the two pits close, nearly 1,500 jobs will be lost at
Easington, and a further 900 jobs will be lost at Vane Tempest.
Both collieries have had considerable financial difficulties. Vane Tempest
made a loss of Pounds 922,000 in the first six weeks of this financial year,
mainly because the colliery had failed to open enough new coal faces to
maintain output.
At Easington production has improved and losses have been reduced since
January, but Mr Brian Wright, group director for the region, said in
February that the pit had to sustain its performance to stay open.
Mr Tom Watson, manager of Westoe colliery, which has been mainly profitable
since the mid 1980s, said last week he might be able to offer jobs to miners
made redundant.
