FT  01 JUN 92 / Charity funds for Tories attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Charity Commission has backed a complaint about a registered charity's
funding of the Conservative party in elections for Westminster City Council.
Mr Andrew Dismore, leader of the Labour opposition on the council,
complained to the commission about the Foundation for Business
Responsibilities making payments to Marketforce Communications, a
public-relations company.
The company was employed by Westminster council's Conservatives to promote
their party before the May 1990 local elections, in which the Tories
increased their majority over Labour on the council.
The commission's rules bar charities from engaging in political activities.
The foundation was established in 1972 as an educational trust.
In a letter to Mr Dismore, the commission said the charity paid more than
Pounds 98,000 to Marketforce, and the payment infringed charity rules. The
money has been repaid to the charity by its trustees, although yesterday it
was still not clear where the refund came from.
Mr Dismore said yesterday that he was seeking an Inland Revenue
investigation into the foundation to discover if it has breached laws
concerning tax relief for charities.
He has also written to Dame Shirley Porter, the Conservative leader of the
council at the time of the payments, asking for clarification of her
involvement with the use of the charity's funds for politically motivated
public-relations work for her party.
A representative of Dame Shirley, who is abroad on holiday, yesterday denied
that she had any connection with the foundation.
</TEXT>
