<DOCNO>FT922-5274</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFAA4AC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920601
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 92 / UN Sanctions Against Serbia: Moves to end trade and freeze
assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING links between the Serbian-led remnant of Yugoslavia and the rest of
the world were severed yesterday, one day after the UN Security Council
imposed a package of comprehensive sanctions.
In Britain, the Treasury moved early today to block Serbian assets, saying
this would take effect from midnight last night. There may be some problems
as banks try to disentangle assets held by Serbia and its ally Montenegro,
the target of sanctions, and the other former Yugoslav states.
The trade ban in Britain meant some 50-60 UK companies which have acquired
export licences to supply goods to Serbia and Montenegro will be told today
these have been revoked. The government has to obtain an order in council
under the Emergency Powers Act letting the Bank of England issue notices to
the commercial banks freezing assets. Similar measures imposed when Iraq
invaded Kuwait were taken within 24 hours. Yugoslavia has been reducing
assets held overseas in expectation of sanctions; assets in the UK are now
thought to be less than Dollars 500m (Pounds 277.7m) against nearly Dollars
600m in June 1991.
The freeze would apply to assets held on behalf of government bodies, banks
and commercial organisations. It was not clear if this covered private
individuals' assets. Trade sanctions cover exports to and imports from
Serbia and Montenegro, and any activity meant to promote trade with those
countries. Goods already shipped and imports already in transit will be
allowed to complete their journeys.
Airline flights to and from those destinations are also barred under the UN
sanctions. In Belgrade the Tanjug news agency said Germany, Switzerland and
the Netherlands had enforced the ban. UK exports to Yugoslavia amounted to
Pounds 194m in 1991 against imports from that country of Pounds 148m. The
top five export categories included telecommunications equipment (Pounds
32m).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
